AGI - It is opening a "new era of bilateral relations between the United States and Kenya>". An era that sees Washington increasingly recognize the strategic importance of the African continent and Nairobi to become "the most important non-NATO ally in the United States". The Council for Foreign Relations >(Cfr), US think tank specializing in foreign policy, after the first warm face-to-face of yesterday between Kenya President William Ruto and US President Joe Biden.&nbsp;&nbsp;>
&nbsp;
&nbsp;A meeting defined by several "historical" parts and not only because Ruto is the first African leader of the last 15 years received with all honors at the White House >: In fact, Joe Biden decided to announce during this first prolonged visit (initiated on Monday in Georgia) "the project to designate Kenya as the main ally of the United States not belonging to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)>", said the White House.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
Kenya notes the Cfr, "is the first country in sub-Saharan Africa to receive this designation, which comes after the two countries have strengthened their defence partnerships in Africa and in other realities" (such as Haiti, where Kenya will lead an UN mission).
" Yesterday - the analysis continues - the leaders discussed a series of economic and security issues in the context of the common will to strengthen technological partnerships > and give a boost to trade". Cfr's experts suggest that U.S. officials "will also work to ensure that Kenya can become the first African country to secure the funding of the Chips and Science Act>&nbsp; (the five-year American plan of almost $250 billion for investment in research and development of semiconductors in order to reduce dependence on China). &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;

<br A move with the aim of "resolving the problem with the US supply chain," said Bloomberg as an American anonymity officer. &nbsp;&nbsp;The two leaders, in the margin of the first day of meetings, held a joint press conference. Ruto was also honored with a state dinner, a treatment that is not always reserved for foreign leaders visiting Washington.&nbsp; "His visit to the United States - it still highlights the Cfr citing US officials - also underlines the objectives and concrete commitments made by the United States with Africa in the broad sense." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<br> Biden also announced that the two countries are launching "a new era of technological cooperation". The latter will include partnerships in the equally strategic areas of artificial intelligence, computer security, clean energy and semiconductors.&nbsp; For his part, they observe analysts, Ruto flew to America with "the priority to guarantee new financial opportunities to a Kenyan economy suffering from heavy debt and a crisis of cost of life". It seems in fact difficult - they add - that the Beijing loans, in the matter of debt, can save the Kenyan accounts. &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;<br> Again, experts stress that the visit to Ruto State reflects "the centrality of Kenya in Africa-USA relations". The British Study Centre Chatham House also notes that "the choice of Kenya by President Biden for the first African State visit is not a coincidence" but rather points to a "increasing strategic dependence".&nbsp;"With Ruto - writes Fergus Kell of Chtham House - Biden welcomes an increasingly assertive international leader, with a curriculum promoting African solidarity and a strong awareness of the new possible partnerships in a multi-faceted world".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<br The state visit gives US politicians and the Kenyan delegation (more than 30 ministers and government officials) "the opportunity to strengthen the foundations for a long-term partnership, but the terms of the talks will obviously be based on the recognition of reciprocal needs", concludes the analyst.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
